      border: 5px solid maroon;
      border-radius: 10px;
      font-size: 24px;
      font-weight: bold;
      font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
    }

    /* Class Selector */
    .first_class {
      color: maroon;
      background-color: yellowgreen;
    }

    /* ID Selector */
    #second_class_id {
      color: whitesmoke;
      background-color: black;
    }

  </style>
</head>

<body>

  <center>
    <h1>This is first CSS class</h1>
  </center>

  <p class="first_class">
    This is our first surprise box
  </p>

  <p id="second_class_id">
    This is our second surprise box
  </p>

  <p>This is our third surprise box</p>
  <p>This is our fourth surprise box</p>

</body>
</html>



✅ Priority Order (Highest to Lowest)
1. Inline CSS  (Highest priority)
2. Internal CSS
3. External CSS (Lowest priority)



📄 priority.css (External CSS)
h1 {
  color: red;
}



📄 HTML File
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
  <title>CSS Priority</title>

  <!-- External CSS -->
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="./priority.css">

  <!-- Internal CSS -->
  <style>
    h1 {
      color: green;
    }
  </style>

</head>

<body>

  <!-- Inline CSS -->
  <h1 style="color: gray;">
    This is CSS priority comparison class
  </h1>

</body>
</html>



What Happens Here?
->External CSS says → red
->Internal CSS says → green
->Inline CSS says → gray

Final Output Color → gray
Because Inline has the highest priority.


