DAY 6 – FLEXBOX 
What is Flexbox?
📌 Definition
-> Flexbox (Flexible Box Layout) is a CSS layout system
   used to arrange elements in rows or columns.
-> It makes alignment and spacing easier.


🔹 Important Rules of Flexbox
1. Flexbox works on the parent element.
2. We apply: display: flex; to the parent.
3. By default, flex-direction is row.


Basic Flexbox Example (Column Layout)
Parent = div


Children = p tags


display: flex applied to div



<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
  <title>Flexbox Example</title>

  <style>
    /* Styling child boxes */
    p {
      color: whitesmoke;
      background-color: black;
      height: 200px;
      width: 200px;
      font-size: 20px;
      text-align: center;
      border-radius: 16px;
    }

    /* Parent container */
    div {
      display: flex;

      /* Default is row */
      flex-direction: column;

      /* Align items vertically (cross-axis) */
      align-items: center;
    }

  </style>
</head>

<body>

  <div>
    <p>First</p>
    <p>Second</p>
    <p>Third</p>
    <p>Fourth</p>
  </div>

</body>
</html>



🔹 Flexbox Axes Understanding
Main Axis:
→ Controlled by flex-direction
→ If row → X-axis
→ If column → Y-axis

Cross Axis:
→ Opposite direction of main axis


🔹 justify-content
-> Used to align items on the MAIN axis.

Examples:
justify-content: start;
justify-content: center;
justify-content: end;
justify-content: space-between;
justify-content: space-around;
justify-content: space-evenly;



🔹 align-items
-> Used to align items on the CROSS axis.

Examples:
align-items: start;
align-items: center;
align-items: end;



