What is Position in CSS?
Definition
The position property specifies how an element
is positioned in a webpage.

Types of Position
1. static  (Default)
2. relative
3. absolute
4. fixed
5. Sticky





position: static (Default)
Definition
-> Static is the default position.
->Elements follow normal document flow.
->Top, left, right, bottom do NOT work.
Example
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.box {
 position: static;
 background: lightblue;
 top: 50px; /* This will NOT work */
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="box">Static Box</div>

</body>
</html>

📌 It behaves normally. No movement.

position: relative
Definition
-> Moves element relative to its original position.
-> Top, left, right, bottom WILL work.
-> Space remains reserved.

Example
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.box {
 position: relative;
 left: 50px;
 top: 20px;
 background: lightgreen;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="box">Relative Box</div>

</body>
</html>

📌 It shifts from original position but keeps its space.

position: absolute
Definition
-> Moves element relative to nearest positioned parent.
-> If no positioned parent, it uses body.
-> Space is NOT reserved.
Example
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.parent {
 position: relative;
 height: 200px;
 border: 2px solid black;
}

.child {
 position: absolute;
 top: 20px;
 right: 20px;
 background: orange;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="parent">
 <div class="child">Absolute Box</div>
</div>

</body>
</html>

📌 It removes element from normal flow.

position: fixed
Definition
-> Element stays fixed on screen.
-> It does NOT move when scrolling.
Example
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.box {
 position: fixed;
 bottom: 20px;
 right: 20px;
 background: red;
 color: white;
 padding: 10px;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="box">Fixed Button</div>

<p style="height:2000px;">Scroll down to see effect</p>

</body>
</html>

📌 It stays at same position while scrolling.

position: sticky
Definition
-> Acts like relative until a scroll limit is reached.
-> Then it becomes fixed.
Example
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.header {
 position: sticky;
 top: 0;
 background: yellow;
 padding: 10px;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="header">Sticky Header</div>

<p style="height:2000px;">
Scroll down to see sticky effect.
</p>

</body>
</html>

📌 It sticks to top when scrolling.

